{"id":"d=origam-topic-4292//p=6b6b961549e44f748a6f27d2f055732f","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4292"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["6ef0d66405ca47c0b6787a3a8fe0e8ff"],"__file_part":["d3d8172818e443579036aeaeed96dbd8"],"__part_n":["3"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"category":["docs"],"categoryId":["8"],"topicId":["4292"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-a-simple-api/4292"],"title":["How to create a simple API"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"520\u00D7620 79.2 KB         \n \n    In ORIGAM, the  PUT  command is used for both record creation and updating. The  PATCH  method is currently not used. \n \n When a PUT request is sent, there are two possible scenarios: \n A record with the specified Id \n \n already exists \u2014 it will be updated, \n does not exist \u2014 it will be created. \n \n In both cases, follow these steps: \n \n Include the Id in the URL, e.g.: \n PUT https://localhost/api/public/task/5784a17e-15fe-4f1e-b612-6a35055f4c0c  \n Create a separate parameter for the request body in your model: \n         image  707\u00D7386 71 KB         \n Include the complete record structure in the request body \u2014 exactly as returned by the GET command, including all brackets and  \u0022ROOT\u0022 , for example: \n \n  {\n  \u0022ROOT\u0022: {\n    \u0022Task\u0022: [\n      {\n        \u0022Status_Id\u0022: \u0022376ae614-1381-4ff5-b894-9c96c7978ead\u0022,\n        \u0022Name\u0022: \u0022Create accounts\u0022,\n        \u0022AssignedTo_Id\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022DueDate\u0022: \u00222025-11-30T00:00:00\u002B01:00\u0022,\n        \u0022Priority_Id\u0022: \u0022bae03329-491c-4b09-8345-f8d26f027e9b\u0022,\n        \u0022NotificationSent\u0022: false,\n        \u0022Description\u0022: \u0022Create user accounts for all new users who joined this month\u0022,\n        \u0022Selected\u0022: false,\n        \u0022RecordCreated\u0022: \u00222025-02-18T13:56:18.073\u002B01:00\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordUpdatedBy\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022Id\u0022: \u00225784a17e-15fe-4f1e-b612-6a35055f4c0c\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordCreatedBy\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordUpdated\u0022: \u00222025-11-06T10:10:30.447\u002B01:00\u0022\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n  \n \n   If you include only some fields in the request body, the remaining fields will be set to  null  or lost. Therefore, if you intend to update only specific fields (similar to a PATCH request), you must still provide the full record data and modify only the fields you wish to change. \n \n   Delete a record \n To enable record deletion via the API, set  AllowDELETE  to  True  in your API configuration. \n When a DELETE request with a valid Id is sent, the corresponding record will be deleted. \nFor example, this request: \n DELETE https://localhost/api/public/task/5784a17e-15fe-4f1e-b612-6a35055f4c0c  \nwill delete the record with that Id, if it exists. No request body is required. \n   Other API types \n In addition to the content above, several other types of APIs are listed below: \n  Workflow Page  \n\n---\n\n@vikter (2026-04-09 13:53:05Z):\n   Workflow Page API type \n This type of API is used to trigger a  sequential workflow  in the application. The settings are similar to the Data Page type but here is also a specification of the workflow that this function is supposed to trigger: \n          Workflow page settings  493\u00D7487 68.2 KB         \n Data can also be passed to this workflow via parameter mapping. For example, JSON is passed here as  InputData , which is then stored in the workflow\u2019s context store for further use:","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-04-29T00:22:49"},"vector":[-0.046132784,-0.013356334,-0.070159905,0.015190387,-0.026415685,-0.02499336,-0.0076